        <div class="post">
          <div class="post-head">
            <div class="title-wrap">
              <h2>Vasilis van Gemert — Exclusive Design</h2>
              <div class="meta">
                <span>Type: Review / Video recap</span>
                <span aria-hidden="true">•</span>
                <span>Topic: Accessibility & design</span>
              </div>
            </div>

            <span class="tag" title="Category">
              <!-- tiny icon -->
              <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                <path d="M20 7H4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                <path d="M20 12H4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                <path d="M20 17H4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round"/>
              </svg>
              Design Thinking
            </span>
          </div>

          <div class="content">
            <p>In his talk “Exclusive Design,” Vasilis van Gemert challenges the way designers usually think about accessibility and inclusive design. He argues that in modern digital products, accessibility is often treated as an addition that comes after the main design is already completed. Designers typically create interfaces for the “average” user and only later try to adapt them for people with disabilities. According to van Gemert, this approach rarely produces truly usable experiences for those who need accessibility the most.</p>

            <p>Instead of simply adding accessibility features on top of existing designs, he proposes a different way of thinking, which he calls Exclusive Design. This concept may sound contradictory, because design discussions often focus on inclusivity. However, van Gemert explains that by designing specifically and intentionally for people with particular needs, designers can discover new, creative solutions that ultimately improve the experience for everyone.</p>

            <p>He shares examples from his work with people who rely on screen readers and other assistive technologies. These cases demonstrate that many conventional design rules and visual hierarchies do not work well for users who interact with interfaces in non-visual ways. Standard layouts, navigation patterns, and interaction models that seem logical to sighted users can become confusing or even unusable for others. This shows that simply following common design conventions is not always the best solution.</p>

            <p>Van Gemert outlines several principles that guide Exclusive Design. First, designers should carefully study the specific situation of the users they are designing for, understanding the real challenges they face. Second, they should be willing to ignore established design conventions when those conventions do not serve the user’s needs. Third, designers should prioritize the identity and personal context of users rather than treating them as a generic audience. Finally, he encourages adding elements of experimentation or “nonsense,” meaning unexpected or unconventional ideas that can lead to more intuitive and accessible solutions.</p>

            <p>Through this approach, van Gemert emphasizes that accessibility should not be a technical checklist but a creative and integral part of the design process. By focusing deeply on the needs of a specific group of users, designers can rethink how interfaces work and create solutions that are not only more accessible but also more innovative. In the end, Exclusive Design demonstrates that designing for particular people in specific situations can lead to better design for all.</p>

            <div class="callout">
              <strong>Key takeaway:</strong> Treat accessibility as a creative starting point—designing deeply for specific needs can produce better, more innovative experiences for everyone.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>
